Male":"1383–Deceased","1385–Male":"1385–Deceased","1387–Female":"1387–Deceased","1406–1460":"1406–1460","–Male":"Deceased","1374":"1374","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","Abt 1383":"about 1383","1435":"1435","1358":"1358","ABT 1385":"about 1385","ABT 1387":"about 1387","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Thurstanston, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Thurstaston, Cheshire, England":"Thurstaston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Thurstaston, Cheshire, England":"Thurstaston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chester","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Chester, the county seat of Cheshire, or from any of various smaller places called with this word (as for example Little Chester in Derbyshire, Chester le Street in County Durham, or Chesters in Northumberland), which is from Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘Roman fort or walled city’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cheshire","meanings":["English: habitational name for someone from the county of Cheshire in northwestern England, the name of which is early recorded as <i>Cestrescire</i>, from the name of the county seat,   Chester  , + Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘district, division’."]},{"name":"Chesterman","meanings":["English: possibly a topographic name for someone who lived by a Roman fort, Old English <i>ceaster</i>, or a habitational name for someone from any of the places mentioned at   Chester  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Chester was born in 1360, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married John de Whitmore in 1374, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1420, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1360–1420":"1360–1420","1358–1438":"1358–1438","1381–1435":"1381–1435","1383–Male":"1383–Surnud","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1406–1460":"1406–1460","–Male":"Surnud","1374":"1374","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","Abt 1383":"umbes 1383","1435":"1435","1358":"1358","ABT 1385":"umbes 1385","ABT 1387":"umbes 1387","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Thurstanston, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Thurstaston, Cheshire, England":"Thurstas